Extracting formant values with Praat

Jason Grafmiller

01 October, 2020

1 Annotating sound files with TextGrids

1.1 Install Praat

The first thing to do is download Praat www.praat.org by following the instructions provided on the website. Praat is a stand-alone executable, which means it does not need to be installed on your machine to run. Simply run Praat.exe.

Praat is an open-source software for acoustic analysis that was developed by Paul Boersma at the University of Amsterdam. The website has lots of helpful tutorials.

1.2 Create a TextGrid

Open the sound file that you will annotate by clicking the Open tab and selecting Read from file... (or type CTRL/CMD+O). Select you file and open it, and you should see it in the Objects: window in Praat. Click on the file name in this window to select it (it should be selected by default after you open it). On the right side, click on the button that says Annotate - and select To TextGrid... option. You should see something like this:

The script outputs a .txt file that we will use to plot our vowel spaces.

You can open this file in Excel or any other text editor and look at it yourself.

3 Plotting the vowel space

Now that we have the data, its very easy to plot the F1 and F2 values for each vowel. Well start with the monophthongs: /i, , , , u, , , /.

This looks like a typical distribution of American English vowels. These are perhaps a bit more dispersed (spread out) due to the nature of the wordlist task, as I was carefully articulating each sound to make them as distinct as possible. In more casual speech wed probably find slightly different values for some vowels, e.g.the vowel in hawed.

A few things we might note:

  • My /u/ vowel in whod is a bit further to the left (a higher F2) than we might find for other American English varieties. This is possibly a reflection of an ongoing change in some varieties of American English, where the /u/ and /o/ vowels are fronting, i.e.their articulation is moving farther forward in the mouth. (Well see how this compares to British English below)
  • My vowel in had is perhaps a bit farther forward (again, higher F2) than we might see in others vowel spaces. This is again an aspect of my American accent. In many British accents this vowel is farther back.
  • My pronunciation of the vowel in hawed here is probably not representative of my actual speech. Again, I was hyperarticulating these sounds in the task here. Typically hawed would rhyme with hod for me (or think of hottie vs.haughty, which are identical for many Americans). General American English has largely lost the contrast between the vowels in words such as cot and caught, which are pronounced identically in General American English. Linguists thus refer to this change as the cot-caught merger. Vowel mergers are generally a very common type of language change, and other examples of mergers in English include the well-known merger of the vowels in foot and strut in Northern England, and the merger of vowels in look and Luke in some Scottish accents. If you want to really have fun, ask people how they pronounce the words merry, marry, and Mary (theyre all the same to me!)

3.1 All speakers

Below is the plot of everyones vowels (or at least those from whom I have data)

Again, this looks pretty good, and there are some fun patterns that are worth pointing out.

Take for example the case of the vowel whod in blue. We have a curious kind of split within the class between those whose vowel is fairly far backDana, Pak, myselfand those whose vowel is relatively farther forwardGabi, Kathryn, Megan, Penny, and Rosie (Julia is a puzzling case That Ill return to below). Whats interesting is that the latter group are (almost) all speakers of British English, while those in the other group are not. I mentioned the fact that my own accent shows evidence of fronting of the vowel in whod, but it turns out this change in American English has nothing on British English, where many varieties outside the North have undergone a rather substantial shift over the last 50 years or so towards a very fronted vowel (see e.g.Strycharczuk & Scobbie 2017). You should be able to hear the difference in my pronunciation of whod compared to those of Megan and Penny.
